(104, 'its-probably-not-aliens-new-oumuamua-theory-suggests-simpler-origins', 'Its probably not aliens: New Oumuamua theory suggests simpler origins', '<p>here&rsquo;s a frozen, interstellar object about half a mile long whizzing through our solar system right now, and nobody has had a particularly clear idea about what it is &mdash; until now. According to a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://news.agu.org/press-release/interstellar-object-oumuamua-is-likely-a-piece-of-a-pluto-like-planet\" target=\"_blank\"><ins>study</ins></a>&nbsp;published Tuesday in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1029/2020JE006706\" target=\"_blank\"><ins>Journal of Geophysical Research</ins></a>, it could be a chunk of a Pluto-like planet from another solar system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s called &lsquo;Oumuaumua, a Hawaiian word meaning &ldquo;scout&rdquo; or &ldquo;messenger from afar&rdquo; in honor of its sighting from the Haleakalā Observatory in Hawaii. The strangely shaped interloper may have once been a piece of a solid nitrogen exoplanet that was sent careening in our direction after an impact roughly 500 million years ago. This new theory is one of the most compelling to come out since &lsquo;Oumuamua&rsquo;s presence was&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mashable.com/2017/11/20/interstellar-asteroid-studied-for-first-time-vega-contact/\"><ins>first noticed in 2017</ins></a>&nbsp;and implies that other solar systems develop in a way similar to our own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rocketing through space at a speed of 196,000 miles per hour, &lsquo;Oumuamua is the first object originating from outside of our solar system that scientists have been able to observe. It has puzzled scientists because it moved like a frozen, dusty comet formed in the colder, outer parts of solar systems, but it didn&rsquo;t have that signature tail of gas and dust behind it. Others speculated that it was a rocky asteroid formed closer to a sun.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>A clearer explanation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>It turns out there may have been a comet-like gas tail streaming behind &lsquo;Oumuamua as the sun melted its surface, but it wasn&rsquo;t detected on the visible light spectrum. That gas tail created a propulsion effect that pushed it slightly off course of what scientists would expect if it was only affected by gravity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We looked at several different ices and the push they would give &lsquo;Oumuamua as they evaporated,&rdquo; the study from authors Alan Jackson and Steven Desch reads. &ldquo;We found that the best ice is nitrogen (N2), which would explain many of the things we know about it. &lsquo;Oumuamua was small, about half as long as a city block and only as thick as a three story building, but it was very shiny. The shininess is about the same as the surfaces of Pluto and Triton [Neptune&#39;s largest moon], which are also covered in nitrogen ice.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A nitrogen composition could account for the interloper&rsquo;s strange shape.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;As the outer layers of nitrogen ice evaporated, the shape of the body would have become progressively more flattened, just like a bar of soap does as the outer layers get rubbed off through use,&rdquo; Jackson said in the press release.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some illustrations depicting &lsquo;Oumuamua don&rsquo;t have that round, flat, cookie-like shape though. Previous illustrations have looked more like long, oblong cigars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Much of the speculation around the shape of &lsquo;Oumuamua comes from the fact that scientists didn&rsquo;t really get a good look at it, said Tom Barclay, a research scientist at the University of Maryland, Baltimore County and NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, in an interview.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It was moving very quickly and so by the time we were able to start a lot of the observations, it was already relatively faint,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&lsquo;Oumuamua had already passed around the other side of the sun from Earth&rsquo;s vantage point when scientists first observed it, making it faint and difficult to observe with definitive accuracy. But if this new study is correct, it would mean &lsquo;Oumuamua has melted into a more pancake-like shape, Barclay said.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>It&rsquo;s not aliens</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Given the object&rsquo;s puzzling characteristics, one astronomer at Harvard put forward the idea that &lsquo;Oumuamua was in fact a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucedorminey/2021/02/11/harvard-astronomer-views-interstellar-interloper-as-humanitys-wake-up-call/?sh=ac709e14a215\" target=\"_blank\"><ins>piece of alien technology</ins></a>&nbsp;moving through our solar system. Part of the theory stems from &lsquo;Oumuamua&rsquo;s trajectory, which could be explained through the use of propulsion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;In spacecraft we launch, we use propulsion to move them and change their trajectory,&rdquo; Barclay, the NASA research scientist, said. &ldquo;We call these thrusters, they&#39;re firing little bursts of material and it pushes spacecraft in certain directions.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comets experience a similar effect when they travel close to stars. Solar energy heats up their frozen materials and they sublimate into gas, giving comets a slight push in a direction away from the star just like &lsquo;Oumuamua&rsquo;s trajectory. This is not at all unusual, Barclay said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SEE ALSO:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mashable.com/article/mars-moons-split/?utm_cid=a-seealso\">Mars&#39; 2 weird moons began as 1 large moon, study suggests</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mashable.com/article/how-to-prove-alien-life/\">search for extraterrestrial life</a>&nbsp;inside and outside our own solar system is a key objective of space research and an important area of study, it isn&rsquo;t necessarily prudent to cry &ldquo;aliens&rdquo; whenever something isn&rsquo;t immediately made clear with a natural explanation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I think it&#39;s important to examine all the evidence before you jump to aliens,&rdquo; Barclay said. &ldquo;Up until now, the answer has never been aliens &hellip; I think before getting excited about aliens, you really want to study and rule out other explanations for this.&rdquo;</p>\r\n', '3460-alien.webp', 'tech', '12', 'John Doe', '1001', 'approved', '2021-03-18 22:00:43'),
(105, 'tech-executives-arent-fortunetellers', 'Tech executives arent fortunetellers', '<p>People who work in technology are often incredibly smart. But that doesn&rsquo;t necessarily make them accurate forecasters of human and social behaviour.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This past week, Airbnb&rsquo;s chief executive said that he thought more people would hop between multiple homes when the pandemic ends. Mark Zuckerberg of Facebook talked about his vision of people using goggles that read their minds. A co-founder of Stripe, the digital finance startup, spoke about a range of things, including worker productivity metrics and the need for improved medical technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These were thought-provoking ideas, and successful tech executives have been right an awful lot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But I am asking for a little more humility from technologists and a little more skepticism from the rest of us. Being really smart and overseeing products used by millions of people doesn&rsquo;t make tech executives oracles. (That&rsquo;s true even for the tech company named Oracle.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As tech has become more enmeshed in our lives and the economy &mdash; and as tech founders have become red-carpet-worthy celebrities &mdash; people want to know what technologists think about &hellip; everything: the future of cities, education, health care, jobs and the environment. It makes sense. I want to hear what they think, too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seeing the activity of millions or billions of people and businesses gives technology companies insights that few others have. We want powerful corporate leaders to be thoughtful about the world. And technologists can turn their beliefs into our reality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But like all of us, technologists have blind spots and biases. They can misjudge or opine on topics that they don&rsquo;t really understand. And humans are not always good at understanding humans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem, I fear, is that we too often associate running an innovative company with an ability to predict the future. And that can have real consequences if we build policy and our lives around what they say.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the most glaring examples was Uber&rsquo;s proclamations that it would help alleviate traffic and pollution in major metropolitan areas and reduce the number of cars in the United States. In 2015, Uber&rsquo;s co-founder, Travis Kalanick, described the future of his company: &ldquo;Fewer cars, less congestion, more parking, less pollution and creating thousands of jobs.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Research now shows that Uber and other on-demand ride services largely did the opposite. They made traffic in many cities worse, contributed to an increase in miles driven in the United States and pulled people from shared transit to solo cars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps Kalanick and others who backed Uber&rsquo;s vision of a less car-reliant country didn&rsquo;t mean it. Maybe they just wanted to make Uber sound virtuous.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But more likely, the lesson here is that technologists often don&rsquo;t foresee how people will respond to what they create. Zuckerberg now says that he didn&rsquo;t anticipate that Facebook would empower authoritarians and create incentives for the most radical voices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some of the same promises that Uber was making a few years ago are now coming from companies working on computer-driven cars, fast trains and other transportation innovations. I&rsquo;m excited about these ideas, but also mindful what happened to the original hope of the ride services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That track record calls not for cynicism but for healthy doubt and self-criticism. We need more questions asked, both by the technology companies and the rest of us. We could start with: What makes you think that? What if you&rsquo;re wrong? What might you be missing?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It might also help if technologists answered, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; when someone asks them to weigh in on China&rsquo;s gross domestic product.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Geopolitics Under the Sea</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I wrote in Wednesday&rsquo;s newsletter about the blurry line between countries&rsquo; desire for technology self-reliance and protectionism. Now I want to make the connection to undersea cables. (As regular On Tech readers know, I love boring technology.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of us will never see the cables that run under oceans and seas, but a few hundred of these pipelines move nearly all international internet and telephone traffic around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That makes the people and companies that control the undersea cables the masters of the internet. They wield choke points that could be abused to spy on what&rsquo;s happening online or cut a country off from large swathes of the internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With that kind of power, these dull clusters of glass fibers are of great concern to governments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can see that in the tussle over a new undersea internet cable called Peace that is snaking from China to Pakistan and then underwater around Africa to France.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This cable is being built by Chinese companies, and US security officials worry that Peace could be used by China&rsquo;s government for sabotage or surveillance. France says the undersea link will help its economy, and it&rsquo;s stuck in the middle between its US allies and China.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Wall Street Journal also reported Wednesday that a group led by Facebook dropped its plans to build a new internet cable between California and Hong Kong after months of pressure from US national security officials. Again, the officials&rsquo; concern is that a physical link to Hong Kong &mdash; and China&rsquo;s greater assertion of control over the island &mdash; could be a security risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fights over undersea cables raise a messy question about technology in a fractured world: Is there a way to connect people without laying the foundation for security threats? Shared internet infrastructure has been essential to link the world, but it doesn&rsquo;t work if countries do not trust one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&copy; 2021 The New York Times Company</p>\r\n', '2612-bd1.jpg', 'tech', '12', 'John Doe', '1001', 'approved', '2021-03-18 22:17:10');

